Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany must now be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don't think she supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical to Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the voting on the establishment of a no-flight zone.
In the end, NATO made this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, moving from a policy that the US has managed to a German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the lack of coherent unified policies among Europeans.
So the Germans are back between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that for the time being they have only felt their role, but they are on the road to "more normal" foreign policy.
The foreign policy of France or Britain.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It is a willingness to take a position in their national interest that is independent of the position of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policies, i.e. exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests differ significantly from those of other major States, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Did these economic interests affect the position in the Middle East conflict and vote in the United Nations?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to insult the public and elites in the Arab countries.
Anyway, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't give it too much importance, it's not entirely one-sided.
But in any case, it plays an important role in German calculations.
Did Germany harm its relationship with the US by refraining from making important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I'm sure in Europe and even in the United States there is a greater understanding of the German position.
That's why I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
This signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be considered.
There are differing views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the other hand, the United States has made clear its support for the veto.
Are there differences between the US and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama Government has a strong understanding of the European position.
